[1] China (Hong Kong ex Thailand)
Date: 15 Aug 2006 21:27:47 -0400
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source:News.gov.hk, 15 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://www.news.gov.hk/en/category/healthandcommunity/060815/html/060815en05004.htm>

The Centre for Health Protection has confirmed dengue fever in a 26 year
old Sha Tin man, bringing the year's total cases to 19, all imported. The
man came down with fever on 14 Jul 2006 after a trip to Thailand. He was
admitted to Union Hospital on 17 Jul 2006 and was transferred to Prince of
Wales Hospital on July 19. He was discharged on 24 Jul 2006.
People should stay alert to the threat of dengue fever and take measures
against mosquito breeding. Travelers should wear long-sleeved tops and
trousers, and use insect repellent. If feeling unwell after returning from
abroad, consult a doctor.
******
[2] China (Hong Kong ex Malaysia)
Date: 17 Aug 2006 22:31:28 -0400
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News.gov.hk, 16 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://www.news.gov.hk/en/category/healthandcommunity/060817/html/060817en05004.htm>

The Centre for Health Protection is investigating a dengue fever case
involving a 28 year old Tsim Sha Tsui woman, bringing the year's total
cases to 20, all imported. She came down with fever on August 10 after
traveling to Malaysia and Indonesia. She was admitted to Union Hospital on
August 14 and is now in stable condition.
******
[3] China (Hong Kong ex Mainland China)
Date: 22 Aug 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News.gov.hk, 22 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://www.news.gov.hk/en/category/healthandcommunity/060822/html/060822en05007.htm>

The Centre for Health Protection is investigating a dengue fever case
involving a 62 year old Ma On Shan man, bringing the year's total cases to
22, all imported. He came down with fever on 1 Aug after traveling to the
Mainland 1 Jul to 28 [Jul 2006]. He recovered after seeking treatment at
Prince of Wales Hospital.
--
ProMED-mail
<Promed@promedmail.org>
[The 3 cases referred to above, along with the 19 imported cases not
reported, provide a vivid illustration of how dengue viruses move around in
areas where the _Aedes_ vectors are present. One cannot help but wonder how
many imported cases go undiagnosed and unreported in the world's tropics.
It would be interesting to know which dengue virus serotypes were involved
in these 3 cases. - Mod.TY]
******
[4] Cambodia
Date: 23 Aug 2006 06:59:53 -0400
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Monsters and Critics.com, UK, 22 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://news.monstersandcritics.com/health/article_1193058.php/Five_Cambodians_die_hundreds_hospitalized_in_dengue_epidemic>

A hospital official said on Tuesday that 5 Cambodian children had died and
nearly a thousand more had been hospitalized as underequipped provincial
health centres and impoverished parents face a rare strain of the virus.
Chrang Narith, deputy chief of the Dengue Fever Unit at Kampong Cham
provincial hospital in the country's east, said outbreaks of the
mosquitoborne disease had reached epidemic proportions since January,
especially in 2 districts of the province, and health authorities feared
more deaths were to come.
"Poor parents wait until the last minute to bring children to the hospital
for treatment, and we just don't have the facilities to successfully treat
children when they have reached that point," Narith said, adding that
treatment costs a minimum of 12 [US] dollars.
He said 5 children had died since April [2006] and 800 had been
hospitalized at the province's major public hospital since January.
Children from Kampong Siem and Kong Meas districts have made up the bulk of
the patients, he said, blaming the outbreak on heavy monsoon rains that
have left plenty of the clean, still water that the mosquito that carries
the disease favours for breeding. Dengue experts have said an unusually
high infection rate with a normally less prevalent strain of the disease
had also contributed to the high number of hospitalizations because
Cambodian children who had not been exposed to the strain lack immunity to it.
Severe cases can become dengue hemorrhagic fever, which is especially
serious in young children and is characterized by spontaneous bleeding from
orifices as blood platelet levels plummet. The usual treatment includes
blood transfusions, but Narith said blood supplies were at a premium.
"The Health Ministry has distributed Abate to the affected areas, and
health experts have gone to the villages to inform people about how the
disease is spread and why children need expert treatment," he said. Abate
is a non-toxic chemical that prevents mosquitos from breeding in still
water, such as water pots and rice paddies.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Abate is an insecticide that has low toxicity for vertebrate animals. Rice
paddies are not a significant breeding habitat for _Aedes aegypti_, which
breeds in containers containing water in and immediately around human
habitations. ProMED-mail requests information about the "rare strain" of
virus cited above, and how it compares to the dengue virus serotypes and
isolates from previous years and other areas in Cambodia.
A map of Cambodia can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/cambodia_pol_97.jpg> -
Mod.TY]
