[5] Bhutan
Date:25 Aug 2006 04:23:14 -0400
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: One World South Asia, 2 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://southasia.oneworld.net/article/view/137314/1/>

Phuentsholing in Bhutan could be on the brink of another dengue fever
outbreak, warn health officials of the Phuentsholing hospital's malaria
unit. It was therefore extremely important that residents cooperated to
clean up and maintain hygienic surroundings. In a span of 17 days, starting
July 11 [2006], 8 dengue cases were reported to the hospital, increasing
the number of cases to 31.
A random sample collection done by the malaria unit officials 4 days ago
found out that the larvae of the dengue-[transmitting] _Aedes_ mosquitoes
were everywhere.
According to health officials the patients were mostly those who went for
morning and evening jogging and walks and spent time outdoors in the
evenings. The backyards of houses in lower market area were littered and
neglected. "There are empty tins, plastic, blocked drains where rain water
collects which make it conducive for mosquito breeding," said an official
during city cleanliness and hygienic living conditions awareness workshop
organised by the women's association, yesterday.
These were man-made breeding sites and since building owners were mostly in
Thimphu the surroundings were neglected, officials said. They pointed out,
during the meeting, that despite their instructions nothing was done by
some business entities.
Residents were made aware of the risk and notified through the local cable
network and selected pockets of the city sprayed with insecticide (thermal
fogging) 3 times during the period 22-24 Jul [2006].
Health officials say that residents should also take preventive measures
such as applying repellent oil or cream and by wearing full-sleeved shirts
and full pants to prevent mosquito bites and anyone suffering from fever,
backache and bleeding gums should immediately report to the hospital.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This is the first ProMED-mail dengue posting for Bhutan, although Bhutan
health officials indicate that dengue has occurred there before. This is
another illustration of the ubiquity of dengue in the tropics. - Mod.TY]
