[6] El Salvador
Date:24 Aug 2006 04:13:08 -0400
From:A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Prensa Latina, Havana, Cuba, 24 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://www.plenglish.com/Article.asp?ID=%7B4D377103-A9F1-4EFC-A749-7AF4129A483F%7D&language=EN>

El Salvador was in a state of emergency on Wednesday due to an increase in
dengue infections reported in several departments, in contrast to the
optimism recently expressed by the government.
According to sources in the Health Ministry that issued the red alert, 471
cases and serotypes (a group of closely related microorganisms with similar
antigens) not reported in the country since 2002 have been confirmed.
Minister Guillermo Maza revealed that 3 out of every 4 infected patients
live in the departments of San Salvador, La Libertad and Sonsonate, and
announced that the [red alert is intended to reduce further spread].
Meanwhile, governmental reports show that the last time this disease forced
the Executive to decree a state of emergency was 4 years ago, and at that
time it only affected 4 departments. Despite authorities' efforts, the
official number of [adult deaths?] was 11, while so far 4 minors have died.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[ProMED-mail requests information concerning the dengue virus serotype(s)
circulating in this outbreak. A map of El Salvador can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/el_salvador.gif>. - Mod.TY]
