[7] Nicaragua
Date: 30 Aug 2006 10:22:22 -0400
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: People's Daily Online / Xinhua [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/200608/30/eng20060830_298119.html>

The Nicaraguan Health Ministry on Tuesday announced measures to prevent
type-3 dengue fever from entering the country as more than 5000 people are
suffering the disease in nearby El Salvador.
El Salvador borders Honduras, which shares a border with Nicaragua. Juan
Jose Amador, director of the ministry's hygiene and epidemiology
department, said that at present, Nicaragua has only 538 confirmed cases of
classic dengue fever and 22 cases of hemorrhagic dengue fever: [dengue
viruses] type 1 and 2.
"We have reinforced preventative actions in the whole of north of the
country, such as fumigating vehicles and homes as well as sending samples
to specific laboratories," Amador said. The ministry said the [dengue virus
]type-3 disease had not appeared in Nicaragua in the last 7 years, and that
the health authorities feared there will be serious problems if type 3
dengue fever enters the country.
Because the type-3 disease has not been found throughout much of the
Americas for about 20 years, most people have a low immunity to the virus,
the authorities said. In 1994, Nicaragua found 19 000 cases of type-3
dengue fever,with several deaths reported.
Dengue fever is a serious health problem in many Central American and
Caribbean countries. Its symptoms include high fever, nausea, rash,
backache, and headache.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Although the Nicaraguan director of the Ministry of Health's Hygiene and
Epidemiology Department indicated that dengue virus type 3 was the one
circulating in neighboring El Salvador (see posting [6] above), it has not
been confirmed by the El Salvador Ministry of Health.
ProMED-mail awaits with interest news of the effectiveness of the
Nicaraguan efforts to keep dengue virus type 3 out of the country. - Mod.TY]
