[8] Dominican Republic
Date: 24 Aug 2006 04:13:08 -0400
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: People's Daily Online, China, 24 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/200608/24/eng20060824_296426.html>

The Dominican Republic's secretary of state for public health, Bautista
Rojas Gomez, said on Wednesday [23 Aug 2006] that at least 17 people have
died of hemorrhagic dengue fever so far in 2006, according to reports from
Santo Domingo.
Rojas told Dominican Television that he is worried about the rising number
of hemorrhagic dengue fever cases, and many of the deaths could have been
avoided, but added that at least the mortality rate is reduced from 2005.
Rojas said that every 5 years, a massive outbreak of the mosquito-spread
fever claims many lives. This year, the epidemic has affected the National
District, Santo Domingo province, San Cristobal, San Francisco de Macoris
and Moca.
In 2005, the Dominican Republic reported 248 cases of dengue fever, 82 of
which were hemorrhagic dengue. This year, 130 cases of normal dengue fever,
and 69 cases of the hemorrhagic one have been recorded.
--
