[9] Cuba
Date: 24 Aug 2006
From: ProMED-Mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC Mundo, La Habana [translation by Mod. TY; edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/hi/spanish/latin_america/newsid_5288000/5288068.stm>

A dengue epidemic is affecting various neighborhoods in Havana, according
to what BBC Mundo was able to gather from different sources which confirmed
these facts, despite the Cuban press not having provided any information
regarding it.
"In the center where I work they said that more than 3000 cases have been
reported for the whole city, and they have said that the municipalities
that have been most affected by the foci [of dengue cases] are Cerro and
Playa," a young worker informed us.
A physician from the Ministry of Health, who wished to remain anonymous,
corroborated to the BBC that there exists an explosion of dengue cases and
that "these [cases] are occurring in the whole city of Havana."
"We have taken all the [necessary] measures; we have various hospitals --
the IPK, the "Salvador Allende" and "La Dependiente", among others, with
dengue units having a total of 800 beds ready to receive patients," the
specialist told us.
[Dengue virus] type 3
---------------------
The serotype involved is dengue [virus type] 3, and according to these
reports there have been few cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever [DHF], the
version [of the dengue virus infection] most lethal. The virus is
transmitted by _Aedes aegypti_, which is very common in the tropics.
The authorities have quickly mobilized an enormous contingent of people in
order to contain foci of _Aedes aegypti_. This contingent visits houses
one-by-one, orienting the population about preventive measures. Moreover,
thousands of workers from the Capital and from other provinces circulate
thoughout the city, having the residents leave their houses and fumigating
these residences house-by house. "We have been working full-time for weeks
in order to eradicate these foci, and in El Cerro we detected 146 [foci?]
already," one of the workers informed us.
Control measures
----------------
Normally, Cuba maintains a permanent control group dedicated to carrying
out preventive measures and fumigation to avoid a resurgence of dengue
foci. Nevertheless, due to various factors, every once in a while the
number of dengue cases shoots up and it is necessary to take additional
measures to avoid epidemics which can lead to the death of patients. In
fact, the first large epidemic of DHF was in 1981, when thousands of people
were infected and hundreds of Cubans lost their lives.
[byline: Fernando Ravsberg]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This is an unofficial report, and the information is not from the Cuban
Ministry of Health. ProMED-mail requests information from the Cuban
Ministry of Health about specific numbers of cases over time and the dengue
virus serotypes that are involved. A progress report on the _Aedes aegypti_
control campaign would also be appreciated. A map of Cuba may be accessed
at <http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/cuba.pdf>.
WHO describes dengue fever as a severe, flu-like illness that affects
infants, young children and adults, but seldom causes death.
The clinical features of dengue fever vary according to the age of the
patient. Infants and young children may have a non-specific febrile illness
with rash (although some infants and very young children may develop shock
syndrome, with sudden loss of circulating fluid volume, and die). Older
children and adults may have either a mild febrile syndrome or the
classical incapacitating disease, with abrupt onset and high fever, severe
headache, pain behind the eyes, muscle and joint pains, and rash.
Dengue hemorrhagic fever is a potentially deadly complication that is
characterized by high fever, hemorrhagic phenomena -- often with
enlargement of the liver -- and in severe cases, circulatory failure. The
illness commonly begins with a sudden rise in temperature accompanied by
facial flush and other non-specific constitutional symptoms of dengue
fever. The fever usually continues for 2 to 7 days and can be as high as
40-41 C [104-105.8 F], possibly with febrile convulsions and hemorrhagic
phenomena.
In moderate DHF cases, all signs and symptoms abate after the fever
subsides. In severe cases, the patient's condition may suddenly deteriorate
after a few days of fever; the temperature drops, followed by signs of
circulatory failure, and the patient may rapidly go into a critical state
of shock and die within 12-24 hours or quickly recover following
appropriate volume replacement therapy.
There is no specific treatment for dengue fever. However, careful clinical
management by experienced physicians and nurses frequently saves the lives
of DHF patients. With appropriate intensive supportive therapy, mortality
may be reduced to less than one percent. Maintenance of the circulating
fluid volume is the central feature of DHF case management.
<http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs117/en/>
ProMED-mail thanks the contributors to this update. - Mod.TY]
